[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] The software was previously called just "PhoneGap", then "Apache Callback".
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] PhoneGap was Adobe's commercial version of Cordova along with its associated ecosystem.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] Many other tools and frameworks are also built on top of Cordova, including Ionic, Monaca, VoltBuilder, TACO, Onsen UI, GapDebug, App Builder, Cocoon, Framework7, Quasar Framework, Evothings Studio, NSB/AppStudio, Mobiscroll, and Telerik Platform.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] These tools use Cordova, and not PhoneGap for their core tools.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] Contributors to the Apache Cordova project include Adobe, BlackBerry, Google, IBM, Intel, Microsoft, Mozilla, and others.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] PhoneGap was first developed by Nitobi Software at an iPhoneDevCamp event in San Francisco in August 2008.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] Apple Inc. has confirmed that the framework has its approval, even with the change to clause 3.3.1 of the Apple iPhone SDK developer license agreement 4.0 adopted in 2010.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] The PhoneGap framework is used by several mobile application platforms such as Monaca, appMobi, Convertigo, ViziApps, and Worklight as the backbone of their mobile client development engine.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] Adobe acquired Nitobi Software on October 3, 2011.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] The PhoneGap code was subsequently contributed to the Apache Software Foundation to start a new project called Apache Cordova.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] The project's original name when submitted to the Apache Software Foundation, Callback, was changed to Cordova for ease in searching the web.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] It also appears in Adobe Systems as *Adobe PhoneGap* and also as *Adobe PhoneGap Build*.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] Early versions of PhoneGap required an Apple computer to create iOS apps and a Windows computer to create Windows Mobile apps.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] After September 2012, Adobe's PhoneGap Build service allows programmers to upload CSS, HTML, and JavaScript source code to a "cloud compiler" that generates apps for every supported platform.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] The core of an Apache Cordova application uses CSS3 and HTML5 for rendering and JavaScript for logic.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] HTML5 provides access to underlying hardware such as the accelerometer, camera, and GPS.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] However, browsers' support for HTML5-based device access is not consistent across mobile browsers, particularly older versions of Android.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] To overcome these limitations, Apache Cordova embeds the HTML5 code inside a native WebView on the device, using a foreign function interface to access the native resources of it.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] Apache Cordova can be extended with native plug-ins, allowing developers to add more functionalities that can be called from JavaScript, making it communicate directly between the native layer and the HTML5 page.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] These plugins allow access to the device's accelerometer, camera, compass, file system, microphone, and more.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] However, the use of Web-based technologies leads some Apache Cordova applications to run slower than native applications with similar functionality.
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] As of version 11, Apache Cordova currently supports development for the operating systems Apple iOS, Google Android, Windows 8.1, Windows Phone 8.1, Windows 10 and Electron (software framework) (which in turn runs on Windows, Linux and macOS).
[src:capacitor-native/apache-cordova] Earlier version of Apache Cordova used to support Bada, BlackBerry, Firefox OS, LG webOS, Microsoft Windows Phone (7 and 8), macOS, Nokia Symbian OS, Tizen (SDK 2.x), and Ubuntu Touch.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:capacitor-native/hybrid-app] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] In computer science, **interprocess communication** (**IPC**) is the sharing of data between running processes in a computer system, or between multiple such systems.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] Mechanisms for IPC may be provided by an operating system.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] Applications which use IPC are often categorized as clients and servers, where the client requests data and the server responds to client requests.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] Many applications are both clients and servers, as commonly seen in distributed computing.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] IPC is very important to the design process for microkernels and nanokernels, which reduce the number of functionalities provided by the kernel.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] Those functionalities are then obtained by communicating with servers via IPC, leading to a large increase in communication when compared to a regular monolithic kernel.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] IPC interfaces generally encompass variable analytic framework structures.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] These processes ensure compatibility between the multi-vector protocols upon which IPC models rely.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] An IPC mechanism is either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] Synchronization primitives may be used to have synchronous behavior with an asynchronous IPC mechanism.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:capacitor-native/inter-process-communication] Different approaches to IPC have been tailored to different software requirements, such as performance, modularity, and system circumstances such as network bandwidth and latency.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] The mobile app development sector has experienced significant growth in Europe.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] A 2017 report from the Progressive Policy Institute estimated there were *1.89 million jobs* in the *app economy* across the European Union (EU) by January 2017, marking a 15% increase from the previous year.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] These jobs include roles such as mobile app developers and other positions supporting the app economy.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] To facilitate developing applications for mobile devices, and the consistency thereof, various approaches have been taken.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Most companies that ship a product (e.g., Apple, iPod/iPhone/iPad) provide an official software development kit (SDK).
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] They may also opt to provide some form of software testing and/or quality assurance (QA).
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] In exchange for being provided the SDK or other tools, it may be necessary for a prospective developer to sign some form of non-disclosure agreement (NDA), which restricts the sharing of privileged information.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] As part of the development process, mobile user interface (UI) design is an essential step in the creation of mobile apps.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Mobile UI designers consider constraints, contexts, screen space, input methods, and mobility as outlines for design.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Constraints in mobile UI design, which include the limited attention span of the user and form factors such as a mobile device's screen size for a user's hand(s).
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Mobile UI context includes signal cues from user activity, such as the location where or the time when the device is in use, that can be observed from user interactions within a mobile app.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Such context clues can be used to provide automatic suggestions when scheduling an appointment or activity or to filter a list of various services for the user.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] The user is often the focus of interaction with their device, and the interface entails components of both hardware and software.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] User input allows for the users to manipulate a system, and the device's output allows the system to indicate the effects of the users' manipulation.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Overall, mobile UI design's goal is mainly for an understandable, user-friendly interface.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Functionality is supported by mobile enterprise application platforms or integrated development environments (IDEs).
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Developers of mobile applications must also consider a large array of devices with different screen sizes, hardware specifications, and configurations because of intense competition in mobile hardware and changes within each of the platforms.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Today, mobile apps are usually distributed via an official online outlet or marketplace (e.g., Apple: The App Store – Google: Google Play) and there is a formalized process by which developers submit their apps for approval and inclusion in those marketplaces.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Historically, however, that was not always the case.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Mobile UIs, or front-ends, rely on mobile back-ends to support access to enterprise systems.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] The mobile back-end facilitates data routing, security, authentication, authorization, working off-line, and service orchestration.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] This functionality is supported by a mix of middleware components, including mobile app servers, mobile backend as a service (MBaaS), and service-oriented architecture (SOA) infrastructure.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] The software development packages needed to develop, deploy, and manage mobile apps are made from many components and tools which allow a developer to write, test, and deploy applications for one or more target platforms.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] First party tools include official SDKs published by, or on behalf of, the company responsible for the design of a given hardware platform (e.g., Apple, Google, etc.), and any third-party software that is officially supported for the purpose of developing mobile apps for that hardware.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] With bring your own device (BYOD) becoming the norm within more enterprises, IT departments often need stop-gap, tactical solutions that layer atop existing apps, phones, and platform component.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Many system-level components are needed to have a functioning platform for developing mobile apps.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Criteria for selecting a development platform usually include the target mobile platforms, existing infrastructure, and development skills.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] When targeting more than one platform with cross-platform development, it is also important to consider the impact of the tool on the user experience.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Performance is another important criterion, as research on mobile apps indicates a strong correlation between application performance and user satisfaction.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Along with performance and other criteria, the availability of the technology and the project's requirements may drive the development between native and cross-platform environments.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] To aid the choice between native and cross-platform environments, some guidelines and benchmarks have been published.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Typically, cross-platform environments are reusable across multiple platforms, leveraging a native container while using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript for the user interface.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] In contrast, native environments are targeted at one platform for each of those environments.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] For example, Android development occurs in the Eclipse IDE using Android Developer Tools (ADT) plugins, Apple iOS development occurs using the Xcode IDE with Objective-C and/or Swift, Windows and BlackBerry each have their own development environments.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Mobile applications are first tested within the development environment using emulators and later subjected to field testing.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Emulators provide an inexpensive way to test applications on mobile phones to which developers may not have physical access.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] The following are examples of tools used for testing applications across the most popular mobile operating systems.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] According to a 2020 Industry Report on Applications, 46% of mobile app users have stated that they have stopped using or uninstalled an app due to poor performance.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Many patent applications are pending for new mobile phone apps.
[src:capacitor-native/mobile-app-development] Most of these are in the technological fields of business methods, database management, data transfer, and operator interface.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] A **progressive web application** (**PWA**), or **progressive web app**, is a type of web app that can be installed on a device as a standalone application.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] PWAs are installed using the offline cache of the device's web browser.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] PWAs were introduced from 2016 as an alternative to native (device-specific) applications, with the advantage that they do not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] They can be used on a range of different systems, including desktop and mobile devices.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Publishing the app to digital distribution systems, such as the Apple App Store, Google Play, or the Microsoft Store on Windows, is optional.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Because a PWA is delivered in the form of a webpage or website built using common web technologies including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and WebAssembly, it can work on any platform with a PWA-compatible browser.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] As of 2025, PWA features are supported to varying degrees by Google Chrome, Apple Safari, Brave, Firefox for Android, Microsoft Edge, and Firefox for Windows.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] At Apple's Worldwide Developers Conference in 2007, Steve Jobs announced that the iPhone would "run applications created with Web 2.0 Internet standards".
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] No software development kit (SDK) was required, and the apps would be fully integrated into the device through the Safari browser engine.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] This model was later switched to the App Store, as a means of appeasing frustrated developers.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] In October 2007 Jobs announced that an SDK would be launched the following year.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] As a result, although Apple continued to support web apps, the vast majority of iOS applications shifted toward the App Store.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Beginning in the early 2010s dynamic web pages allowed web technologies to be used to create interactive web applications.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Responsive web design, and the screen-size flexibility it provides have made PWA development more accessible.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Continued enhancements to HTML, CSS, and JavaScript allowed web applications to incorporate greater levels of interactivity, making native-like experiences possible on a website.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] It was intended to be an open-source operating system for running web apps as native apps on mobile devices.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Firefox OS was based on the Gecko rendering engine with a user interface called Gaia, written in HTML5.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] The development of Firefox OS ended in 2016, and the project was completely discontinued in 2017, although a fork of Firefox OS was used as the basis of KaiOS, a feature phone platform.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Google then put significant efforts into promoting PWA development for Android.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Firefox introduced support for service workers in 2016, and Microsoft Edge and Apple Safari followed in 2018, making service workers available on all major systems.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] By 2019, PWAs were supported by desktop versions of some browsers, including Microsoft Edge (on Windows) and Google Chrome (on Windows, macOS, ChromeOS, and Linux).
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] In December 2020, Firefox for desktop abandoned the implementation of PWAs (specifically, removed the prototype "site-specific browser" configuration that had been available as an experimental feature).
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] A Firefox architect noted: "The signal I hope we are sending is that PWA support is not coming to desktop Firefox anytime soon." Mozilla supports PWAs on Android and plans to keep supporting it.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Firefox version 143.0, released in September 2025, added support for PWA on Windows.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps are all designed to work on any browser that is compliant with the appropriate web standards.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] As with other cross-platform solutions, the goal is to help developers build cross-platform apps more easily than they would with native apps.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps employ the progressive enhancement web development strategy.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Some progressive web apps use an architectural approach called the App Shell Model.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] In this model, service workers store the Basic User Interface or "shell" of the responsive web design web application in the browser's offline cache.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] This model allows for PWAs to maintain native-like use with or without web connectivity.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] This can improve loading time, by providing an *initial static frame*, a layout or architecture into which content can be loaded progressively as well as dynamically.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] There are many technologies commonly used to create progressive web apps.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] A web application is considered a PWA if it satisfies the installation criteria, thus can work offline and can be added to the device's home screen.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] To meet this definition, all PWAs require at minimum a manifest and a service worker.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Other technologies may be used to store data, communicate with servers or execute code.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] This metadata is crucial for an app to be added to a home screen or otherwise listed alongside native apps.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] iOS Safari partially implements manifests, while most of the PWA metadata can be defined via Apple-specific extensions to the meta tags.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] These tags allow developers to enable full-screen display, define icons and splash screens, and specify a name for the application.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] A service worker is a web worker that implements a programmable network proxy that can respond to web/HTTP requests from the main document.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] It is able to check the availability of a remote server, cache content when that server is available, and serve that content to the document later.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Service workers, like any other web workers, work separately from the main document context.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Service workers can handle push notifications and synchronize data in the background, cache or retrieve resource requests, intercept network requests and receive centralized updates independently of the document that registered them, even when that document is not loaded.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Service workers go through a three-step lifecycle of Registration, Installation and Activation.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Registration involves telling the browser the location of the service worker in preparation for installation.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Installation occurs when there is no service worker installed in the browser for the web app, or if there is an update to the service worker.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Activation occurs when all of the PWA's pages are closed, so that there is no conflict between the previous version and the updated one.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] The lifecycle also helps maintain consistency when switching among versions of a service worker since only a single service worker can be active for a domain.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] WebAssembly allows precompiled code to run in a web browser, at near-native speed.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Thus, libraries written in languages such as C can be added to web apps.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Announced in 2015 and first released in March 2017, WebAssembly became a W3C recommendation on December 5, 2019 and it received the Programming Languages Software Award from ACM SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] is a WHATWG standard API that enables key–value storage in modern browsers.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] (that enables storage that persists across sessions).
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] is a W3C standard database API available in all major browsers.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] objects and any structures representable as a string.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] providing additional constructs around it.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] In 2017, Twitter released Twitter Lite, a PWA alternative to the official native Android and iOS apps.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] According to Twitter, Twitter Lite consumed only 1–3% of the size of the native apps.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Starbucks provides a PWA that is 99.84% smaller than its equivalent iOS app.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] After deploying its PWA, Starbucks doubled the number of online orders, with desktop users ordering at about the same rate as mobile app users.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] A 2018 review published by Forbes, found that users of Pinterest's PWA spent 40% more time on the site compared to the previous mobile website.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Ad revenue rates also increased by 44%, and core engagements by 60%.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Flipkart saw 60% of customers who had uninstalled their native app return to use the Flipkart PWA.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Lancôme saw an 84% decrease in time until the page is interactive, leading to a 17% increase in conversions and a 53% increase in mobile sessions on iOS with their PWA.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Since a PWA does not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms and is available to users via the web, it is not necessary for developers to release it over digital distribution systems like the Apple App Store, Google Play, Microsoft Store, or Samsung Galaxy Store.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] The major app stores support the publication of PWAs to varying degrees.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Google Play, Microsoft Store, and Samsung Galaxy Store support PWAs, but Apple App Store does not.
[src:capacitor-native/progressive-web-app] Microsoft Store publishes some qualifying PWAs automatically (even without app authors' requests) after discovering them via Bing indexing.
[src:capacitor-native/webview] A **WebView** is a web browser that is embedded within an app.
[src:capacitor-native/webview] Thus, a WebView is a large-scale software component that enables the use of web content within apps.
[src:capacitor-native/webview] In some cases, the entire functionality of the app is implemented this way.
[src:capacitor-native/webview] Other examples are Microsoft's legacy WebView, based on its deprecated EdgeHTML and MSHTML engines, and the WebView component in JavaFX.
